programme.title: DCI Banks
programme.sub-title: Piece of My Heart - Part One
programme.desc: Part one of two. When the body of investigative journalist Matt Barber is found in a holiday chalet in a remote village, Banks and his team are initially confronted by an overwhelming number of leads. As the detective identifies a connection between the victim and a mysterious death in the 1980s connected to the surviving members of a cult rock band, he must begin to unpick decades of lies. To make matters worse, the deceased man's father is former senior police officer Jack Barber, who is now a candidate in the local commissioner elections - and Morton is convinced he is obstructing their inquiry. Stephen Tompkinson stars(n)

programme.title: DCI Banks
programme.sub-title: Piece of My Heart - Part Two
programme.desc: Part two of two. With lawyer David Hornby now a suspect, Cabbot is forced to admit the father of her baby doesn't know about her pregnancy. She then discovers band member Martin Soames' confession in the John Gaunt case file is missing and that Matt Barber's father Jack was the original investigating officer, leading Helen to believe she has the evidence she needs to push the former policeman harder. But when Banks learns of a mysterious tape recording that appears to link Jack with the Crystal Kiss, he realises he's in a race to find it if he is to have any hope of uncovering the truth. Stephen Tompkinson stars(n)

Meanwhile, producer Lucy Freeman chairs a meeting about forthcoming flagship show Britain's Tastiest Village. Hugh Bonneville and Jessica Hynes star, with Carol Vorderman appearing as herself. programme.title: W1A
programme.desc: In the wake of Wingategate, Ian heads north to Salford to appear on Woman's Hour and faces tough questions from Jenni Murray about ageism and sexism regarding the appointment of female presenters. Meanwhile, the Britain's Tastiest Village team discovers at the last minute that the indisposed Clare Balding is unexpectedly available and keen to do the show - but she turns up unannounced for a production meeting and bumps into her replacement Carol Vorderman. Spoof documentary, starring Hugh Bonneville and Jessica Hynes(n)

programme.title: DCI Banks
programme.sub-title: Piece of My Heart - Part One
programme.desc: Part one of two. When the body of investigative journalist Matt Barber is found in a holiday chalet in a remote village, Banks and his team are initially confronted by an overwhelming number of leads. As the detective identifies a connection between the victim and a mysterious death in the 1980s connected to the surviving members of a cult rock band, he must begin to unpick decades of lies. To make matters worse, the deceased man's father is former senior police officer Jack Barber, who is now a candidate in the local commissioner elections - and Morton is convinced he is obstructing their inquiry. Stephen Tompkinson stars(n)

programme.title: DCI Banks
programme.sub-title: Piece of My Heart - Part Two
programme.desc: Part two of two. With lawyer David Hornby now a suspect, Cabbot is forced to admit the father of her baby doesn't know about her pregnancy. She then discovers band member Martin Soames' confession in the John Gaunt case file is missing and that Matt Barber's father Jack was the original investigating officer, leading Helen to believe she has the evidence she needs to push the former policeman harder. But when Banks learns of a mysterious tape recording that appears to link Jack with the Crystal Kiss, he realises he's in a race to find it if he is to have any hope of uncovering the truth. Stephen Tompkinson stars(n)

In this episode, Steve Leonard and his team investigate the best ways to help your pet lose weight, witness a pioneering operation to improve the life of a paralysed Dachshund, decode the secret language of guinea pigs, and discover why, when it comes to rabbits, it is time to ditch the hutch(n)

programme.title: Gardeners' World
programme.desc: An extended edition from Longmeadow and the RHS Malvern Spring Festival. Monty Don plants herbs in his new herb garden and gives advice on how to divide ornamental grasses, while Nick Bailey demonstrates a simple way of making a pond. Jekka McVicar builds a herb garden at the Malvern Show as Carol Klein, Joe Swift and Frances Tophill highlight the best from the floral marquee and show gardens. Including Weather(n)

programme.title: Live Women's FA Cup Football
programme.sub-title: Live Women's FA Cup Final: Birmingham City Ladies v Manchester City Women
programme.desc: Birmingham City Ladies v Manchester City Women (Kick-off 5.15pm). Coverage of the showpiece match from Wembley Stadium, where the FA WSL teams face each other. The Blues recorded a penalty shoot-out victory over Chelsea in the semi-finals to progress to the final for just the second time in their history, with the previous appearance coming in 2012, when they won the trophy in similar fashion by beating Chelsea on spot kicks. Meanwhile, the Citizens will be competing in their first-ever final, after they beat Liverpool 1-0 in the last four. Presented by Tina Daheley, with commentary by Jonathan Pearce and Sue Smith. Subsequent programmes are subject to change(n)

programme.title: Yorkshire Wolds Way
programme.sub-title: Yorkshire Wolds Way with Paul Rose
programme.desc: The first of two programmes in which adventurer Paul Rose explores the 79 miles of the Yorkshire Wolds Way, one of Britain's least well-known national walking trails. The trail starts at the Humber Estuary and ends at the North Yorkshire seaside resort of Filey. On the way, Paul takes in the views from the top of the Humber Bridge, learns to ride a penny farthing and searches out the spots made internationally famous by the artist David Hockney(n)

programme.title: Dad's Army
programme.sub-title: The Day the Balloon Went Up
programme.desc: The platoon rescues the verger from being carried away by a barrage balloon and the men take it off to the woods to secure it to a tree. Unfortunately they let go of the ropes too early and it floats off - taking Captain Mainwaring with it. Classic comedy first broadcast in 1969, starring Arthur Lowe, John Laurie, John Le Mesurier and Clive Dunn(n)

Several art treasures belonging to her family were seized by the Nazis when she escaped, including a famous painting by Klimt, and she enlists the aid of an American lawyer in reclaiming them from the current government. Cynical Madame de Montespan already despairing of her ailing new-born daughter's likely future, tackles the Catholic Church in the form of Father Pascal. Chevalier incites a fight, envious of the attentions Philippe is paying to the King's chronicler Thomas Beaumont. Period drama, starring George Blagden, Jessica Clark and Alexander Vlahos(n)

Trapped in a loveless relationship and at odds with the repressive society she finds herself in, she is driven to desperation and considers poisoning her husband. Drama based on Francois Mauriac's novel, starring Audrey Tautou and Gilles Lellouche. In French(n)

programme.title: Great British Menu
programme.desc: The two remaining South West chefs compete for a place in the national finals, preparing their entire menus for judges Oliver Peyton, Matthew Fort, Andi Oliver and guest judge Marion Regan. Marion's farm provides the famous Wimbledon strawberries to the Championships, so her involvement is entirely suitable given the ongoing tennis theme to the series(n)

Presented by Tanya Arnold, with commentary by Dave Woods, analysis from Jonathan Davies, Brian Noble and Robbie Hunter-Paul, and reports by Damian Johnson(n)

programme.sub-title: Inside the Factory: How Our Favourite Foods Are Made: Bread
programme.desc: Gregg Wallace and Cherry Healey find out about the production of three household staples, beginning with bread. Gregg visits one of Britain's largest bakeries, which makes up to one and a half millions loaves each week, where he sees a machine that can bag a loaf in mid-air. Cherry is at a mill to discover the secret of making the perfect flour and historian Ruth Goodman shows the hidden killers that used to lurk within bread(n)

programme.title: Amazing Hotels: Life Beyond the Lobby
programme.desc: Giles Coren and Monica Galetti travel more than 120 miles north of the Arctic Circle into Swedish Lapland to work in Icehotel in the village of Jukkasjarvi. Using two-ton blocks of ice hacked from the nearby River Torne, Giles works with a team of international artists to create individually crafted rooms and is taught how to make drinking glasses from ice, while Monica learns how the head chef uses natural ingredients found in the nearby forest; and meets Manne, an 82-year-old man who supplies reindeer meat to the hotel. Last in the series(n)

programme.title: Mexico: Earth's Festival of Life
programme.desc: Exploring the forests of the Yucatan Peninsula, which contain the ruins of the Mayan civilisation and a wide range of wildlife, including jaguars, monkeys and tropical birds. The region also holds a secret that is the key to how Mexico's people and animals are able to survive during the country's dry season(n)

programme.title: Dara and Ed's Road to Mandalay
programme.desc: Dara O Briain and Ed Byrne continue their journey in Thailand, where they find out about locals' reaction to the tourist explosion in Bangkok, explore the ruins of the capital of Ayutthaya and visit an elephant sanctuary. Along the way, they stop off for a massage and Ed has a go at Thai boxing. They also visit a turtle conservation centre, where they help to return two of the animals to the sea, and meet members of a hill tribe who have turned their tradition of downhill racing in wooden carts into a tourist attraction(n)

programme.title: Half of a Yellow Sun

Their professional and romantic lives drive them in different directions and a betrayal pushes them further apart - but both are soon drawn into the civil war sweeping the country. Drama based on Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie's novel, starring Thandie Newton, Anika Noni Rose and Chiwetel Ejiofor(n)

programme.title: Memento

Unable to remember events for more than a few minutes, he is determined to track down the killer and relies on copious note-taking and reminders tattooed on his body to aid his mission. Christopher Nolan's thriller, starring Guy Pearce, Carrie-Anne Moss, Joe Pantoliano and Mark Boone Jr(n)

Meanwhile, Dominic struggles with his first day back on Keller when a deceitful patient reminds him of his traumatic relationship with Isaac. Plus, Hermione Cockburn visits the islands around Easdale in Scotland's Firth of Lorn, which hosts the world stone-skimming championship(n)

programme.title: Red Rock
programme.desc: Connor gets more heavily involved with drugs, while Sean has a mystery to solve when a car is found with blood inside it(n)

programme.desc: Si King and Dave Myers prepare dishes from their favourite cookery books, explaining their value as social documents that reveal a great deal about people and what they ate. The duo meet Ivan Day, who has one of the most extensive collections of recipe books in the UK, and share stories of renowned food writers such as Elizabeth David and Isabella Beeton(n)

programme.title: The Wonder of Animals
programme.desc: Chris Packham examines what lies beneath a crocodile's hard exterior, discovering the secret to its ancient history and gaining an insight into one of the most sophisticated physiologies on the planet. By following all stages of a crocodile hunt, Chris reveals how their extraordinary circulatory system enables them to hold their breath for more than an hour, and looks at how their exceptionally sensitive skin detects their prey through water(n)

programme.title: Rise of the Continents
programme.desc: Geologist Professor Iain Stewart examines key moments in the development of the world's major land masses. He begins by looking at how Africa was formed from the wreckage of a long-lost supercontinent, with its landmarks, mineral wealth and wildlife providing clues that help piece together the story of its creation. He also reveals how this deep history has left its mark on modern day Africa and the world(n)

programme.title: Antiques Road Trip
programme.sub-title: Philip Serrell and James Braxton - Day One
programme.desc: Antiques experts Philip Serrell and James Braxton set off on a trip around the south of Scotland as they seek out bargains that will earn them a profit. They begin their journey in Glasgow, which Philip soon flees in favour of the Western Isles, before the pair are reunited again at auction in Edinburgh(n)

programme.desc: Patrick Kielty hosts the quiz, with Alex James, Esther Rantzen and Hal Cruttenden using their knowledge and debating skills to help Cheshire entertainer Billy win a cash prize(n)

The dishes include a salad made up of 10 complex elements, and a cucumber and oyster creation, with a Great British Menu veteran judging their efforts(n)

programme.title: Natural World
programme.desc: Documentary telling how the world's smallest animals manage to survive, revealing how they have evolved extraordinary skills and achieved mindboggling feats. From the animal kingdom's greatest artist to the tiny creatures that provide people with so much of the air they breathe, the programme discovers what it takes to be a miniature miracle. Hugh Dennis narrates(n)

programme.title: The Day the Dinosaurs Died
programme.desc: Documentary examining whether an asteroid strike 66 million years ago triggered a worldwide catastrophe, killing off the dinosaurs and wiping out 75 per cent of all life on Earth. Evolutionary biologist Ben Garrod joins a multimillion pound drilling expedition into the exact spot in the Gulf of Mexico that was the point of impact, while palaeopathologist Alice Roberts meets leading scientists to find if the effects could have wiped out dinosaurs across the world almost immediately(n)

programme.title: Detectorists
programme.desc: New series. Following a chance encounter with a young history student, friends and metal-detecting enthusiasts Lance and Andy embark on a journey towards the discovery of a lifetime. All they need to do is get permission from a local landowner, who is rumoured to have murdered his wife. Comedy, starring Mackenzie Crook and Toby Jones, with Rachael Stirling and Aimee-Ffion Edwards(n)

programme.title: Newsnight
programme.desc: Analysis of the day's events, presented by Emily Maitlis(n)

programme.title: Morocco to Timbuktu: An Arabian Adventure
programme.desc: Writer and explorer Alice Morrison presents the first of two programmes in which she follows the salt roads of North Africa, once the world's richest trading networks, to the fabled sandstone city of Timbuktu. Setting off from Tangier, she learns how the routes were forged by the demand for gold from the mines of sub-Saharan Africa. She then passes through the Islamic city Fes, home to the world's oldest university, catches a train to the great market town of Marrakech and treks across the Atlas Mountains, before visiting the ancient caves of salt, the commodity that gave the roads their name(n)

programme.title: Nature's Great Events
programme.desc: David Attenborough describes the annual melting of more than three million square miles of Arctic sea ice, which can be perilous for indigenous species. He also assesses fears that the region could be ice-free throughout the summer months in 50 years' time, and speculates on the results for native polar bears, whales and guillemot chicks(n)

programme.title: Masters of the Pacific Coast: The Tribes of The American Northwest
programme.desc: Part one of two. Archaeologist Dr Jago Cooper explores the American Northwest, revealing how culture was established on the coast that has lasted for over 10,000 years. He travels to southeast Alaska, British Columbia and Washington State to see how a complex society developed without agriculture, and discloses the hidden significance in totem poles, canoes and intricate textiles(n)

programme.title: Hinterland
programme.desc: A curator named Laura Dean is discovered in a shallow grave in remote woodland, so Mathias and the team delve into the young victim's life, and unearth some shocking secrets. Meanwhile, Brian Prosser, still reeling from the death of Iwan Thomas, calls on the help of retired chief inspector Robert Owen. In English and Welsh(n)

programme.title: The Kate Bush Story: Running Up That Hill
programme.desc: Documentary exploring the singer-songwriter's career and music from her 1978 debut single Wuthering Heights to her 2011 album 50 Words for Snow with testimony from collaborators, fellow artists inspired by her work and fans. Featuring David Gilmour, the guitarist who discovered Bush, as well as Peter Gabriel, Elton John, Stephen Fry, Outkast's Big Boi and Steve Coogan(n)

programme.title: Kate Bush at the BBC
programme.desc: A compilation of the singer's performances at the BBC's studios between 1978 and 1994. Bush appeared on a variety of programmes, including Top of the Pops, Wogan, Ask Aspel, Saturday Night at the Mill and the Leo Sayer Show. Featuring the hits Wuthering Heights, Babooshka, Running Up That Hill and Hounds of Love, as well as intriguing and lesser-known material(n)

Featuring David Gilmour, the guitarist who discovered Bush, as well as Peter Gabriel, Elton John, Stephen Fry, Outkast's Big Boi and Steve Coogan(n)

programme.title: The Birth of British Music
programme.desc: Charles Hazlewood explores the legacy of 18th-century Austrian composer Joseph Haydn, who arrived in Britain aged almost 60, just as the Church's influence on music was diminishing. He discovers how Haydn's passion for science and the cosmos had a profound effect on his work, and travels to Scotland to investigate the composer's association with some of the most famous Scottish folk songs. With pianist Howard Moody and soprano Sophie Daneman(n)

programme.title: Timeshift
programme.sub-title: The Engine That Powers the World: Timeshift
programme.desc: Looking at the surprising story of the diesel engine - a 19th century invention which is the hidden powerhouse behind the globalised world and is now indispensable. Car enthusiast Mark Evans gets hands on with Rudolf Diesel's original creation, including vintage submarines, tractors, locomotive trains and container ships(n)

programme.title: OJ: Made in America
programme.sub-title: OJ: Made in America - Storyville: Part One
programme.desc: New series. Documentary series chronicling the rise and fall of OJ Simpson, and what his story reveals about issues of race, celebrity, the media and the justice system in the US. The first episode explores the history of race relations in California and how this may have influenced public attitudes to Simpson's infamous murder trial, as well as exploring his rise to fame in the world of American football(n)

programme.title: Storyville
programme.desc: The story of Tyke, an elephant who went on the rampage in Honolulu, Hawaii in 1994, killing her trainer in front of thousands of spectators, before dying in a hail of gunfire. Her break for freedom, filmed from start to end, traumatised a city and ignited a global battle over the use of animal in the entertainment industry. This film goes back to meet the trainers and handlers who knew her and witnesses to the rampage(n)

programme.title: Timeshift
programme.sub-title: Timeshift: How Britain Won the Space Race - The Story of Bernard Lovell and Jodrell Bank
programme.desc: The story of how Bernard Lovell turned a field in Cheshire into a key site in the Space Race. Lovell and his telescope at Jodrell Bank enabled the the Americans and the Russians to track their competing spacecraft during the height of the Cold War. This put Britain at the forefront of radio astronomy, a new science which transformed knowlegde of space and provided the key to understanding the beginnings of the universe - the Big Bang(n)

programme.title: Horizon
programme.sub-title: Horizon: The Creative Brain - How Insight Works
programme.desc: The work of scientists who are adopting unusual techniques to try to determine how flashes of inspiration come about, developing a series of puzzles and brainteasers to spark creative behaviour. The latest neuro-imaging technology means researchers can witness the birth of an idea as it happens and what they are learning has the power to make everyone more creative(n)

programme.desc: The Monty Python star sets off on a quest to investigate the story of little-known 17th-century Italian artist Artemisia Gentileschi after one of her paintings caught his eye. Michael encounters her work in Florence, Rome and Naples, and finds out about her life as a working mother and her ultimate success against all odds as a great painter of the Baroque age who transformed the way women were depicted in art, and who was sought after in many courts across Europe(n)

programme.title: 100 Days

programme.title: Insect Worlds
programme.desc: Steve Backshall explores the connections and relationships humans have with insects and their close relatives, the arachnids and crustaceans. He begins by revealing how huge armies of driver ants give houses a five-star clean-up in Kenya, while in China, silkworm caterpillars are credited with shaping culture and distribution. He also explains that, despite people's perceptions of these creepy-crawlies, mankind could not live without them(n)

programme.title: Mud, Sweat and Tractors: The Story of Agriculture
programme.desc: The production of fruit and vegetables in Britain. Archive material filmed by the principal of Waterperry, a college near Oxford, shows how propagation techniques revolutionised strawberry cultivation in the 1960s, while Jersey tomato growers Peter Le Maistre and Stanley Payn explain how their industry was transformed by the commercial glasshouse(n)

programme.desc: Lucy Worsley profiles women who took advantage of social and technological changes during the Restoration era to step into traditionally male roles and challenge British gender divisions. programme.title: Human Planet
programme.desc: Mankind's ability to survive in extreme environments, featuring visits to locations in remote parts of the world to see how people have adapted to their surroundings. The first episode focuses on how humans survive in marine conditions, and provides an insight into the different techniques used by subsistence whalers in Indonesia, fishermen in northern Spain, Brazil and the Philippines, and the Bajau Laut sea gypsies, whose methods include hunting underwater using spears. Narrated by John Hurt(n)

programme.title: Human Planet
programme.sub-title: Arctic - Life in the Deep Freeze
programme.desc: The lives of people in the Arctic, an environment where little food grows, temperatures remain well below freezing for much of the year and it stays dark for months on end. Amos and Karl-Frederik travel across the sea ice with their dogs to catch a Greenland shark, Inuit mussel-gatherers embark on a perilous quest to collect their food and the trick-or-treating children of Churchill, Manitoba, risk coming face to face with polar bears(n)

programme.title: Human Planet
programme.desc: The ingenious survival techniques used by people who live in rainforests, home to more species of plants and animals than any other habitat on Earth. The Matis tribe of Brazil carve blow-pipes to hunt monkeys in almost total silence, while deep in the Congo forests a man scales a giant tree and contends with a swarm of bees to collect honey for his family. Three children from Venezuela's Piaroa tribe search for tarantulas for lunch, and a high-rise home is constructed in West Papua. Narrated by John Hurt(n)

programme.title: Human Planet
programme.desc: The ways in which people survive living at high altitudes, beginning on the Altai Mountains in western Mongolia, where the locals have forged an unusual hunting partnership with golden eagles. On the cliffs of the Simien Mountains in Ethiopia, a boy fights off gelada monkeys intent on stealing his family's grain, while in the Himalayan country of Nepal, the dead are fed to vultures in a rarely seen sky burial. Narrated by John Hurt(n)

programme.title: Human Planet
programme.desc: Survival techniques used by people living on grasslands, including traditional Dorobo hunters in Kenya, who employ a high-risk strategy to benefit from the wildebeest migration. Plus, Namibia's Jo'hansi Bushmen, who wait in hiding for five days to capture a kudu antelope, and modern-day cowboys in Australia who use helicopters to round up more than 20,000 cattle. Narrated by John Hurt(n)

programme.title: Human Planet
programme.desc: The challenges and unpredictable situations faced by people living close to rivers. A man risks his life by crossing the Mekong in Laos during a flood, hoping to reach an island where he can fish for food, while two children and their father trek for nearly six days on a frozen river in the Himalayas. Elephants in Kenya help Samburu tribesmen find water, and villagers in Brazil devise an ingenious solution when the Rio Negro floods their homes(n)

programme.title: Human Planet
programme.desc: An insight into how nature has adapted to life in urban environments, where more than half the world's human population resides. In Dubai, the ancient art of falconry has offered a solution to a 21st-century problem, while in Colorado's Estes Park, the police deal with an invasion of giant elk. Raiding monkeys cause trouble for an Indian fruit seller in Jaipur, and a mother has unwelcome guests in her London home. Narrated by John Hurt. Last in the series(n)

Comedy, starring Eddie Murphy and Kerry Washington(n)

programme.title: Field of Dreams
programme.desc: A farmer hears a mysterious voice inspiring him to mark out a baseball diamond in a cornfield - which, to his surprise, is visited by the ghost of the star player of the 1919 Chicago White Sox team, whose career was cut short by scandal. It later dawns on him the pitch has a greater purpose - to give people who have sacrificed important parts of their lives a second chance. Fantasy, starring Kevin Costner, Ray Liotta, Burt Lancaster and James Earl Jones(n)

programme.title: Gulliver's Travels
programme.desc: A directionless loser tries to prove himself to the woman he loves by volunteering for a travel writing assignment. He is sent to the Bermuda Triangle, where he ends up stranded on an island populated by miniature people to whom he is a giant. Fantasy comedy, starring Jack Black, Emily Blunt, Jason Segel and Billy Connolly(n)

programme.title: The Three Musketeers

Swashbuckling adventure, starring Oliver Reed, Michael York, Richard Chamberlain, Frank Finlay, Charlton Heston and Faye Dunaway(n)

programme.title: I, Robot

Sci-fi thriller, inspired by the Isaac Asimov stories, starring Will Smith, Bridget Moynahan and Alan Tudyk(n)

programme.title: Salt

She goes on the run, with her colleagues in hot pursuit - but each attempt to prove her innocence only raises more questions about her identity. Action thriller, starring Angelina Jolie, Liev Schreiber and Chiwetel Ejiofor(n)

programme.title: The Haunting
programme.desc: Three sleep-deprived people gather at a house haunted by evil spirits to take part in an insomnia study. It soon becomes clear they are really there to aid a scientist's investigation into the origins of fear - and from the very first night, the visitors find themselves facing their deepest and most secret terrors as they confront the unknown forces prowling the corridors. Horror remake, starring Liam Neeson, Lili Taylor, Catherine Zeta-Jones and Owen Wilson(n)

programme.title: Fright Night
programme.desc: A teenager becomes convinced his new next door neighbour is a vampire responsible for a series of recent disappearances. Finding nobody is willing to believe his unlikely story, he seeks the aid of a washed-up movie star famous for playing a vampire hunter in destroying the monster. Comedy horror, starring Chris Sarandon, Roddy McDowall, William Ragsdale, Amanda Bearse and Stephen Geoffreys(n)

programme.title: Rugrats Go Wild
programme.desc: A leaky boat leaves the precocious youngsters stranded on a jungle island, but their luck changes when explorers the Wild Thornberrys come to their rescue. However, Thornberry dad Nigel loses his memory, so it falls to his daughter Eliza to save the day. Children's animated adventure, with the voices of Nancy Cartwright, Bruce Willis, Lacey Chabert, Elizabeth Daily and Tim Curry(n)

programme.title: Spy Kids 4: All the Time in the World
